,"Raby, Durham, England":"Raby, Durham, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","High Worsall Manor, Northallerton, Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":36,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gilbert Hansard II was born about 1179, his father, Gilbert Hansard I, was 46 and his mother, Joan de Stuteville, was 40. He married Avicia Neville before 1205, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1223, in Durham, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1179–about 1223":"umbes 1179–umbes 1223","1179–1223":"1179–1223","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1205–1253":"1205–1253","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1135–1196":"1135–1196","1140–1197":"1140–1197","before 1205":"enne 1205","1253":"1253","1197":"1197","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","Bef 1197":"enne 1197","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1135":"1135","1223":"1223","1179":"1179","Abt 1177":"umbes 1177","1244":"1244","1199":"1199","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1210":"1210","1177":"1177","before 1196":"enne 1196","about 1179":"umbes 1179","about 1223":"umbes 1223","about 1210":"umbes 1210","Durham, England":"Durham, England","Raby, Durham, England":"Raby, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","High Worsall Manor, Northallerton, Yorkshire North Riding, England":"Northallerton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1179–about 1223":"noin 1179–noin 1223","1179–1223":"1179–1223","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1205–1253":"1205–1253","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1135–1196":"1135–1196","1140–1197":"1140–1197","before 1205":"ennen vuotta 1205","1253":"1253","1197":"1197","1196":"1196","1140":"1140","Bef 1197":"ennen vuotta 1197","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1215